result.execSummary:
The defendant Wendell Lamont White was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Wendell Lamont White is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Wendell Lamont White was found guilty of Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).
  • Wendell Lamont White was found guilty of Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Wendell Lamont White appeared by video.  Attorney Matthew V Plummer appeared by video for Wendell Lamont White.  Prosecuting attorney Ryan Jay Michaels appeared by video for the State of Wisconsin. 

Case in court for Plea/ Sentencing hearing.

Parties have reached an agreement. State places offer on the record. Defense and defendant are in agreement.

Amended Information filed.  Copy given to defense counsel who waived reading.  Defendant pled not guilty. 

Pursuant to negotiations and on the Motion of the State, Court Ordered Count 1 DISMISSED OUT RIGHT for the purpose of sentencing.

As to Counts 2 and 3: Defendant changes pleas to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Defendant further advised that if not a US citizen, deportation is possible. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, Addendum, and Elements/Jury Instructions received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's pleas.  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

Parties prepared to proceed with sentencing. State advised the Court they have complied with the Victims' Rights Law. Statements by each counsel and defendant as to sentencing.

As to Count 2: Court sentenced the defendant to serve 90 days in the House of Correction, concurrent to count 3, with Huber release privileges with credit for 6 days served. 
Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for 15 months.

As to Count 3: Court sentenced the defendant to serve 6 months in the House of Correction, concurrent to count 2, with Huber release privileges with credit for 6 days served. 
Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for 15 months.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION:
- Court set restitution at zero.
- Complete batterer's intervention program.
- Complete Parenting Class.
- Complete 50 hours of community service.
- No violent contact with K.A.W. 
- Third party contact for the purpose of time with children as approved by agent. 
- Obtain/maintain employment.
- No contact with firearms.
- Provide a DNA sample during the term of probation.
- Defendant to pay all mandatory costs, assessments and surcharges, including the DV and DNA surcharges during the period of probation. Failure to pay the costs and surcharges will result in a civil judgment.
- Court WAIVED all other court costs, fees, and surcharges due to inability to pay.
- Defendant is eligible for expungement upon successful completion of probation.

*Court advised defendant of appellant rights. 
*Court advised defendant due to this DV conviction he may never possess firearms or ammunition.
*Court ordered defendant to sign up for probation no later than 4:00 pm on 09/02/2022.
*Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession, ammunition, and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored.
